# DataFrame

A DataFrame is the core two-dimensional data structure in the pandas library 
— think of it as a programmable spreadsheet or SQL table in Python.

What it is: A labeled, size-mutable table of rows and columns. 
Each column can hold a different data type (integers, strings, floats, booleans,
etc.), and both rows and columns have labels (an index and column names).

```python
import pandas as pd

# From a dictionary
df = pd.DataFrame({
    "name": ["Alice", "Bob", "Carol"],
    "age": [30, 25, 35],
    "score": [88.5, 92.0, 79.3]
})

```

gives 

|    |name |age|score|
|----|-----|---|-----|
|0   |Alice| 30| 88.5|
|1   | Bob | 25| 92.0|
|2   |Carol| 35| 79.3|

## Key concepts:
Each column is a pd.Series (a one-dimensional labeled array). The row labels form the Index, which defaults to 0, 1, 2… but can be dates, strings, or anything hashable.

##Common operations at a glance:
+ Inspecting — df.head(), df.info(), df.describe(), df.shape, df.dtypes
+ Selecting — df["age"] for a column, df.loc[0] by label, df.iloc[0] by position, df[df["age"] > 25] for filtering.
+ Transforming — df.sort_values("score"), df.groupby("name").mean(), df.apply(func), df.merge(other_df), df.pivot_table(...).
+ Cleaning — df.dropna(), df.fillna(0), df.rename(columns={...}), df.drop_duplicates().
+ I/O — pd.read_csv(), pd.read_excel(), pd.read_sql(), and their df.to_*() counterparts for export.


Why it matters: DataFrames give you vectorized operations (fast, no explicit loops), built-in alignment by labels, and tight integration with the rest of the Python data ecosystem (NumPy, Matplotlib, scikit-learn, etc.). They're the standard starting point for virtually any data analysis or ML pipeline in Python.
